<paragraph blockId="8.[189,1399,1006,1257]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1815" box="[370,442,1006,1032]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Onthophagus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hircus">
<emphasis box="[370,442,1006,1032]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">hircus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group are distributed from the northern United States (Wisconsin according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Howden H. F. &amp; Cartwright O. L." box="[189,545,1044,1071]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the United States National Museum" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 133" part="114" publicationUrl="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00963801.114-3467.1" refId="ref9013" refString="Howden H. F. &amp; Cartwright O. L. 1963. Scarab beetles of the genus Onthophagus Latreille north of Mexico (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae). Proceedings of the United States National Museum 114 (3467): 1 - 133. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.114 - 3467.1" title="Scarab beetles of the genus Onthophagus Latreille north of Mexico (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae)" type="journal article" year="1963">Howden &amp; Cartwright (1963)</bibRefCitation>
; although the authors do not provide the exact locality, its position onto the map appears to be located far north with respect to the Canadian (mostly south of Toronto) and USA localities recorded in our study to central Argentina (San Luís Province), with the highest diversity across the Mexican Transition Zone, as well as the Brazilian and Chacoan sub-regions, which refer to the geographical space occurring from central and southern Mexico to most of continental South America (
<figureCitation box="[306,379,1231,1257]" captionStart="Fig. 4" captionStartId="12.[189,232,2000,2026]" captionTargetBox="[200,1390,770,1960]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[189,1398,763,1966]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 4. Geographical range of the hircus group." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1251604/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
